<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>Note 1 - </B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES <I>(continued)</I>:</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 1in"><B>Effect of New Accounting Pronouncements <I>(continued)</I>:</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">financial instruments and the volatility in earnings caused
by measuring related assets and liabilities differently. They also require entities to display the fair value of those assets and
liabilities. The Company has chosen to use fair value on the face of the balance sheet. The Company does not believe that ASC Topic
825 will have a material impact on its financial statements.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" BORDER="0" STYLE="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>Note 2 - </B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>INVENTORIES:</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">Inventories are stated at cost, on a first-in, first-out
basis, which does not exceed market value.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The Company manufactures products pursuant to specific technical
and contractual requirements. The Company historically purchases material in excess of its requirements to avail itself of favorable
pricing as well as the possibility of receiving additional orders from customers. This excess may result in material not being
used in subsequent periods, which may result in this material being deemed obsolete.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The Company annually reviews its purchase and usage activity
of its inventory of parts as well as work in process and finished goods to determine which items of inventory have become obsolete
within the framework of current and anticipated orders. The Company based upon historical experience has determined that if a part
has not been used and purchased or an item of finished goods has not been sold in three years, it is deemed to be obsolete.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The Company estimates which materials may be obsolete and
which products in work in process or finished goods may be sold at less than cost. A periodic adjustment, based upon historical
experience is made to inventory in recognition of this impairment.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">Inventories are comprised of the following:</P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" BORDER="0" STYLE="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>Note 5 - </B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>ACCOUNTS RECEIVABLE FINANCING:</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The Company has an accounts receivable financing agreement
with a non-bank lending institution (&ldquo;Factor&rdquo;) whereby it can borrow up to 80 percent of its eligible receivables (as
defined in such financing agreement) at an interest rate of 2 &frac12;% above JP Morgan Chase&rsquo;s publicly announced rate with
a minimum rate of 12% per annum.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&nbsp;</P>

    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>Note 5 - </B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>ACCOUNTS RECEIVABLE FINANCING <I>(continued)</I>:</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The financing agreement has an initial term of one year
and will automatically renew for successive one-year terms, unless terminated by the Company or its lender upon receiving 60 days
prior notice. Funds advanced by the Factor are secured by the Company&rsquo;s accounts receivable and inventories. As of March
30, 2012 the Company had reported a liability to the factor of $54,943 compared to March 25, 2011, where the Company had reported
excess payments to the Factor resulting in an overpayment of $78,898, which the Company intends to apply against future borrowings.
These excess repayments are reported in the accompanying financial statements as &ldquo;Excess payments to accounts receivable
factor&rdquo;.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>Note 7 - </B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>INCOME TAXES:</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 0.5in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The Company accounts for income taxes under the provisions
of ASC Topic 740, Income Taxes which includes the provisions of SFAS No. 109 (&ldquo;SFAS 109&rdquo;). Under SFAS 109, deferred
income tax assets or liabilities are computed based upon the temporary differences between the financial statement and income tax
bases of assets and liabilities using the currently enacted marginal income tax rates. Deferred income tax expenses or credits
are based on the changes in the deferred income tax assets or liabilities from period to period.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="mso-special-character: line-break;
page-break-before:
always"></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 45pt">&nbsp;</P>

the actual results could differ from those estimates. Future profitability in this competitive industry depends on continually
obtaining and fulfilling net profitable contracts or the failure of the Company&rsquo;s engineering development efforts could reduce
estimates of future profitability, which could affect the Company&rsquo;s ability to realize the deferred tax assets.</P>

    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>Note 8 -</B> </TD>
    <TD STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>WORKERS COMPENSATION INSURANCE ASSESSMENT: </B></TD></TR>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">On September 15, 2008, the Company was notified by the State
of New York Workers&rsquo; Compensation Board (the &ldquo;Board&rdquo;) that the Trade Industry Workers&rsquo; Compensation Trust
for Manufacturers (the &ldquo;Trust&rdquo;) had defaulted. As a member of this self-insured group, the Company was assessed on
an estimated basis by the Board for its allocable share necessary to discharge all liabilities of the Trust.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The assessed amount for the years 2002 through 2006 was
$101,362. The assessed amount for each year is detailed as follows:</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 0.5in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The Company did have the option of paying this assessment
as a lump sum amount or paying off the assessment over a 60 month period. The Company elected the deferral option, and was obligated
to making monthly payments of $1,689 for 59 months, and $1,711 for the 60<SUP>th</SUP> and final month. The Company had recorded
this assessment as a charge to Cost of Sales in the quarter ended December 26, 2008.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The Company was subsequently notified that it was being
assessed an additional $146,073 covering the years 2002 through 2007, bringing the total deficit allocation assessment to $247,435.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The total received assessment for the years 2002 to 2007
is as follows:</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 2in">&nbsp;</P>

<TR STYLE="vertical-align: bottom; background-color: rgb(204,238,255); font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="width: 86%; text-align: left; padding-left: 5.4pt; vertical-align: bottom; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">2002</TD><TD NOWRAP STYLE="width: 2%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="width: 1%; text-align: left; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">$</TD><TD NOWRAP STYLE="width: 10%; text-align: right; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">23,445</TD><TD NOWRAP STYLE="width: 1%; text-align: left; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">&nbsp;</TD></TR>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" BORDER="0" STYLE="width: 100%; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">

    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">Note 8 - </TD>
    <TD STYLE="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">WORKERS COMPENSATION INSURANCE ASSESSMENT <I>(continued)</I>:</TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><FONT STYLE="text-underline-style: double">&nbsp;</FONT></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The Company has elected to pay the revised assessment over
a five year period (60 months). The monthly payments, inclusive of interest at 7.50%, are $3,970.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">As of March 30, 2012 the remaining balance of the revised
assessment payable was $113,061.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" BORDER="0" STYLE="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>Note 9 -</B> </TD>
    <TD STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>CHANGES IN STOCKHOLDERS&rsquo; EQUITY: </B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The accumulated retained earnings increased by $1,102,424,
which represents the net income for the fiscal year ended March 30, 2012. As a result, the Company reported retained earnings of
$4,929,658.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" BORDER="0" STYLE="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>Note 10- </B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>2011 EMPLOYEE STOCK OPTION PLAN:</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">On August 31, 2011, the Company&rsquo;s shareholders approved
the adoption of the Company&rsquo;s 2011 Equity Incentive Plan (&ldquo;2011 Plan&rdquo;) to provide for the grant of stock options
and restricted stock awards to purchase up to 750,000 shares of the Company&rsquo;s common stock to all employees, consultants
and other eligible participants including senior management and members of the Board of Directors of the Company. The 2011 Plan
replaced the prior 2002 Employee Stock Option Plan which had expired in accordance with its terms.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">Options granted to employees under the 2011 Plan may be
designated as options which qualify for incentive stock option treatment under Section 422A of the Internal Revenue Code, or options
which do not qualify (non-qualified stock options).</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">Under the 2011 Plan, the exercise price of an option
designated as an incentive stock option shall not be less than the fair market value of the Company&rsquo;s common stock on
the day the option is granted. In the event an option designated as an incentive stock option is granted to a ten percent
(10%) or greater shareholder, such exercise price shall be at least 110 percent (110%) of the fair market value of the
Company&rsquo;s common stock and the option must not be exercisable after the expiration of five years from the day of the
grant. The 2011 Plan also provides that holders of options that wish to pay for the exercise price of their options
with shares of the Company&rsquo;s common stock must have beneficially owned such stock for at least six months prior to
the exercise date.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">Exercise prices of non-incentive stock options may be less
than the fair market value of the Company&rsquo;s common stock.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The aggregate fair market value of shares subject to options
granted to a participant(s), which are designated as incentive stock options, and which become exercisable in any calendar year,
shall not exceed $100,000. As of March 30, 2012, no options or restricted stock awards had been granted under the 2011 Plan.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" BORDER="0" STYLE="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>Note 11 - </B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><B>CASH BONUS PLAN:</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">In 1987, the Company adopted a cash bonus plan (&ldquo;Cash
Bonus Plan&rdquo;) for Executive Officers. Contributions to the Bonus Plan are made by the Company only after pre-tax operating
profits exceed $150,000 for a fiscal year, and then to the extent of 10% of the excess of the greater of $150,000 or 25% of pre-tax
operating profits. For the year ended March 30, 2012, the Company&rsquo;s contribution was $149,000. For the year ended March 25,
2011, the Company&rsquo;s contribution was $173,000.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">&nbsp;</P>

through November 30, 2020. The basic minimum annual rentals are as follows:</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The rental expense for the years ended March 30, 2012 and
March 25, 2011, was $149,380 and $133,849, respectively.</P>

<P STYLE="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: center">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The
Company has a collective bargaining multi-employer pension plan (&ldquo;Multi-Employer Plan&rdquo;) with the United Auto Workers
of America, Local 259. Contributions are made in accordance with a negotiated labor contract and are based on the number of covered
employees employed per month. With the passage of the Multi-Employer Pension Plan Amendments Act of 1990 (the &ldquo;1990 Act&rdquo;),
the Company may become subject to liabilities in excess of contributions made under the collective bargaining agreement. Generally,
these liabilities are contingent upon the termination, withdrawal, or partial withdrawal from the Multi-Employer Plan.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">The Company has not taken any action to terminate, withdraw
or partially withdraw from the Multi-Employer Plan nor does it intend to do so in the future. Under the 1990 Act, liabilities would
be based upon the Company&rsquo;s proportional share of the Multi-Employer Plan&rsquo;s unfunded vested benefits, which is currently
not available. The amount of accumulated benefits and net assets of such Plan also is not currently available to the Company. The
total contributions charged to operations under this pension plan were $115,637 for the year ended March 30, 2012 and $110,881
for the year ended March 25, 2011.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" BORDER="0" STYLE="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top; font-family: Times New Roman, Times, Serif; font-weight: bold">
    <TD STYLE="width: 1in; font-family: Times New Roman, Times, Serif; font-weight: bold"><B>Note 13 - </B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="font-family: Times New Roman, Times, Serif; font-weight: bold"><B>REVENUES FROM MAJOR CUSTOMERS:</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">In
the fiscal year ended March 30, 2012 five customers accounted for approximately 50.3% of revenues. During the year ended March
25, 2011 approximately 38% of the Company&rsquo;s total revenues were earned from four customers. Total sales to these customers
were approximately $6,687,000 and $5,240,000. Of these, two customers accounted for 12.15% and 11.83% of the Company&rsquo;s sales
respectively. As of March 30, 2012, amounts due from three customers represented 28% of the total balance of accounts receivable.</P>

<HEAD>
     <TITLE></TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">

<P STYLE="margin: 0"></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt; text-align: center"><B>Exhibit 31.1</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt; text-align: center"><B>CERTIFICATIONS </B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">I, Michael Offerman, certify that:</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0.5in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.5in">1.</TD><TD>I have reviewed this report on Form 10-K of IEH Corporation for the year ended March 30, 2012.</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0.5in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.5in">2.</TD><TD>Based on my knowledge, this report does not contain any untrue statement of a material fact or omit to state a material fact
necessary to make the statements made, in light of the circumstances under which such statements were made, not misleading with
respect to the period covered by this report.</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0.5in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.5in">3.</TD><TD>Based on my knowledge, the financial statements, and other financial information included in this report, fairly present in
all material respects the financial condition, results of operations and cash flows of the registrant as of, and for, the periods
presented in this report.</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0.5in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.5in">4.</TD><TD>The registrant&rsquo;s other certifying officer and I are responsible for establishing and maintaining disclosure controls
and procedures (as defined in Exchange Act Rules 13a-15(e) and 15d-15(e)) and internal control over financial reporting (as defined
in Exchange Act Rules 13a-15(f) and 15d-15(f)) for the registrant and we have:</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">a)&#9;designed such disclosure controls and procedures,
or caused such disclosure controls and procedures to be designed under our supervision, to ensure that material information relating
to the registrant including its consolidated subsidiaries, is made known to us by others within those entities, particularly during
the period in which this report is being prepared; and</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 0.75in">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">b)&#9;designed such internal control over financial reporting,
or caused such internal control over financial reporting to be designed under our supervision, to provide reasonable assurance
regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance
with generally accepted accounting principles; and</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 58.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">c)&#9;evaluated the effectiveness of the registrant&rsquo;s
disclosure controls and procedures and presented in this report our conclusions about the effectiveness of the disclosure controls
and procedures, as of the end of the period covered by this report based on such evaluation; and</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 58.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">d)&#9;disclosed in this report any change in the registrant&rsquo;s
internal control over financial reporting that occurred during the registrant&rsquo;s most recent fiscal quarter (the registrant&rsquo;s
fourth fiscal quarter in the case of an annual report) that has materially affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect
the registrant&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting; and</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0.5in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.5in">5.</TD><TD>The registrant&rsquo;s other certifying officer and I have disclosed, based on our most recent evaluation of internal control
over financial reporting, to the registrant&rsquo;s auditors and the audit committee of registrant&rsquo;s board of directors (or
persons performing the equivalent function); and</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">a)&#9;all significant deficiencies and material weaknesses
in the design or operation of internal control over financial reporting which are reasonably likely to adversely affect the registrant&rsquo;s
ability to record, process, summarize and report financial information; and</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in">b)&#9;any fraud, whether or not material, that involves
management or other employees who have a significant role in the registrant&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 22.5pt">Date: <FONT STYLE="color: black">July 9, 2012</FONT></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 22.5pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 22.5pt"><U>/s/ Michael Offerman</U></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 22.5pt">Michael Offerman, President and Chief Executive Officer
(Principal Executive Officer)</P>

<HEAD>

<BODY STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">

<P STYLE="margin: 0"></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0; text-align: center"><B>Exhibit 32.1</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0; text-align: center">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0; text-align: center"><B>CERTIFICATION PURSUANT TO 18 U.S.C.
SECTION 1350</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0; text-align: center"><B>AS ADOPTED PURSUANT TO SECTION 906
OF</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0; text-align: center"><B>THE SARBANES-OXLEY ACT OF 2002</B></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0; text-align: center">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0">In connection with the Annual Report of IEH Corporation
(the &ldquo;Company&rdquo;) on Form 10-K for the year ending March 30, 2012 as filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission
on the date hereof (the &ldquo;Report&rdquo;), the undersigned, being, Michael Offerman, President and Chief Executive Officer
(Principal Executive Officer), and Robert Knoth, Chief Financial Officer (Principal Accounting Officer), of the Company, respectfully
certify, pursuant to 18 U.S.C. ss.1350, as adopted pursuant to ss.906 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002, that:</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 27pt">(1)</TD><TD STYLE="padding-right: 27pt">The Report fully complies with the requirements of the Section 13(a) or 15(d) of the Securities
Exchange Act of 1934, as amended; and</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 27pt">(2)</TD><TD STYLE="padding-right: 27pt">The information contained in the Report fairly presents, in all material respects, the financial
condition and results of operations of the Company.</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0">Dated: <FONT STYLE="color: black">July 9, 2012</FONT></P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 27pt 0 0">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">This Certification is being furnished solely to accompany the Report
pursuant to 18 U.S.C. Section&nbsp;1350, as adopted pursuant to Section&nbsp;906 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002, and shall not
be deemed &ldquo;filed&rdquo; by the Company for purposes of Section&nbsp;18 of the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, or the
Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, whether made before or after the date of the Report, irrespective of any general incorporation
language contained in such filing. A signed original of the written statement required by Section&nbsp;906 has been provided to
the Company and will be retained by the Company and furnished to the Securities and Exchange Commission or its staff upon request.</P>

    <us-gaap:CompensationRelatedCostsGeneralTextBlock contextRef="From2011-03-26to2012-03-30">&lt;p style="margin: 0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: top; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;td style="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Note 11 - &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;CASH BONUS PLAN:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;In 1987, the Company adopted a cash bonus plan (&amp;#147;Cash&#13;Bonus Plan&amp;#148;) for Executive Officers. Contributions to the Bonus Plan are made by the Company only after pre-tax operating&#13;profits exceed $150,000 for a fiscal year, and then to the extent of 10% of the excess of the greater of $150,000 or 25% of pre-tax&#13;operating profits. For the year ended March 30, 2012, the Company&amp;#146;s contribution was $149,000. For the year ended March 25,&#13;2011, the Company&amp;#146;s contribution was $173,000.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="margin: 0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:CompensationRelatedCostsGeneralTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:InventoryDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="From2011-03-26to2012-03-30">&lt;p style="margin: 0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: top; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Note 2 - &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;INVENTORIES:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Inventories are stated at cost, on a first-in, first-out&#13;basis, which does not exceed market value.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company manufactures products pursuant to specific technical&#13;and contractual requirements. The Company historically purchases material in excess of its requirements to avail itself of favorable&#13;pricing as well as the possibility of receiving additional orders from customers. This excess may result in material not being&#13;used in subsequent periods, which may result in this material being deemed obsolete.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company annually reviews its purchase and usage activity&#13;of its inventory of parts as well as work in process and finished goods to determine which items of inventory have become obsolete&#13;within the framework of current and anticipated orders. The Company based upon historical experience has determined that if a part&#13;has not been used and purchased or an item of finished goods has not been sold in three years, it is deemed to be obsolete.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company estimates which materials may be obsolete and&#13;which products in work in process or finished goods may be sold at less than cost. A periodic adjustment, based upon historical&#13;experience is made to inventory in recognition of this impairment.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Inventories are comprised of the following:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse: collapse; As a member of this self-insured group, the Company was assessed on&#13;an estimated basis by the Board for its allocable share necessary to discharge all liabilities of the Trust.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The assessed amount for the years 2002 through 2006 was&#13;$101,362. margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The rental expense for the years ended March 30, 2012 and&#13;March 25, 2011, was $149,380 and $133,849, respectively.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: center"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The&#13;Company has a collective bargaining multi-employer pension plan (&amp;#147;Multi-Employer Plan&amp;#148;) with the United Auto Workers&#13;of America, Local 259. Contributions are made in accordance with a negotiated labor contract and are based on the number of covered&#13;employees employed per month. With the passage of the Multi-Employer Pension Plan Amendments Act of 1990 (the &amp;#147;1990 Act&amp;#148;),&#13;the Company may become subject to liabilities in excess of contributions made under the collective bargaining agreement. Generally,&#13;these liabilities are contingent upon the termination, withdrawal, or partial withdrawal from the Multi-Employer Plan.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company has not taken any action to terminate, withdraw&#13;or partially withdraw from the Multi-Employer Plan nor does it intend to do so in the future. Under the 1990 Act, liabilities would&#13;be based upon the Company&amp;#146;s proportional share of the Multi-Employer Plan&amp;#146;s unfunded vested benefits, which is currently&#13;not available. The amount of accumulated benefits and net assets of such Plan also is not currently available to the Company. The&#13;total contributions charged to operations under this pension plan were $115,637 for the year ended March 30, 2012 and $110,881&#13;for the year ended March 25, 2011.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="margin: 0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:CommitmentsAndContingenciesDisclosureTextBlock>

    <us-gaap:SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock contextRef="From2011-03-26to2012-03-30">&lt;table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="width: 100%; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: top; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;td style="width: 1in; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Note 1 - &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Description of Business:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company designs, develops and manufactures printed circuit&#13;connectors for high performance applications. The Company has also developed a high performance plastic circular connector line.&#13;All of the Company&amp;#146;s products utilize the HYPERTAC&amp;#153; contact design, which is identified by the generic &amp;#147;HYPERBOLOID&amp;#148;&#13;in the Company&amp;#146;s catalogs. This is necessary since all other HYPERTAC&amp;#153; companies have been purchased by a multi-national&#13;company. The Company is the only independent producer of HYPERTAC&amp;#153; in the United States.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company&amp;#146;s customers consist of OEM&amp;#146;s (Original&#13;Equipment Manufacturers), companies manufacturing medical equipment, and Distributors who resell the Company&amp;#146;s products to&#13;OEMs. The Company sells its products directly and through regional representatives located in all regions of the United States,&#13;Canada, Israel, India, various Pacific Rim countries, South Korea and the European Union (EU).&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The customers the Company services are in the Government,&#13;Military, Aerospace, Medical, Automotive, Industrial, Test Equipment and Commercial Electronics markets. The Company appears on&#13;the Military Qualified Product Listing &amp;#147;QPL&amp;#148; to MIL-DTL-55302 and supply customer requested modifications to this specification.&#13;Sales to the commercial electronic and military markets were 31% and 60%, respectively, of the Company&amp;#146;s net sales for the&#13;year ended March 30, 2012. The Company&amp;#146;s offering of &amp;#147;QPL&amp;#148; items has recently been expanded to include additional&#13;products.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in; text-indent: -1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Accounting Period:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company maintains an accounting period based upon a&#13;52-53 week year, which ends on the nearest Friday in business days to March 31&lt;sup&gt;st&lt;/sup&gt;. The year ended March 30, 2012 was&#13;comprised of 53 weeks and the year ended March 25, 2011 was comprised of 52 weeks.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Revenue Recognition:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Revenues are recognized at the shipping date of the Company's&#13;products. The Company has historically adopted the shipping terms that title merchandise passes to the customer at the shipping&#13;point (FOB Shipping Point). At this juncture, title has passed, the Company has recognized the sale, inventory has been relieved,&#13;and the customer has been invoiced. The Company does not offer any discounts, credits or other sales incentives.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company&amp;#146;s policy with respect to customer returns&#13;and allowances as well as product warranty is as follows:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company will accept a return of a defective product&#13;within one year from shipment for repair or replacement at the Company&amp;#146;s option. If the product is repairable, the Company&#13;at its own cost will repair and return to the customer. If unrepairable, the Company will either offer an allowance against payment&#13;or will reimburse the customer for the total cost of the defective product.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Most of the Company&amp;#146;s products are custom ordered&#13;by customers for a specific use. The Company provides engineering services as part of the relationship with its customers in developing&#13;the custom product. The Company is not obligated to provide such engineering service to its customers. The Company does not charge&#13;its customers separately for these services.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: top; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 1in; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Inventories:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in; text-align: left"&gt;&lt;font style="font-weight: normal"&gt;Inventories&#13;are stated at cost, on a first-in, first-out basis, which does not exceed market value.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in; text-align: left"&gt;&lt;font style="font-weight: normal"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in; text-align: left"&gt;&lt;font style="font-weight: normal"&gt;The&#13;Company manufactures products pursuant to specific technical and contractual requirements. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company historically purchases material in excess of&#13;its requirements to avail itself of&lt;b&gt; &lt;/b&gt;favorable pricing as well as the possibility of receiving additional orders from customers.&#13;This excess may result in material not being used in subsequent periods, which may result in this material being deemed obsolete.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company annually reviews its purchase and usage activity&#13;of its inventory of parts as well as work in process and finished goods to determine which items of inventory have become obsolete&#13;within the framework of current and anticipated orders. The Company based upon historical experience has determined that if a part&#13;has not been used and purchased or an item of finished goods has not been sold in three years, it is deemed to be obsolete. The&#13;Company estimates which materials may be obsolete and which products in work in process or finished goods may be sold at less than&#13;cost. A periodic adjustment, based upon historical experience is made to inventory in recognition of this impairment.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Concentration of Credit Risk:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Financial instruments which potentially subject the Company&#13;to concentrations of credit risk consist primarily of cash and cash equivalents and accounts receivable.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0.3in 0 1in"&gt;Under the provisions of the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform&#13;and Consumer Protection Act that was signed into law on July 21, 2010, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) will permanently&#13;insure interest bearing accounts at financial institutions up to $250,000 in the aggregate.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0.3in 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0.3in 0 1in"&gt;An additional provision of the Dodd-Frank Act provides&#13;for all non-interest bearing transaction accounts to be fully insured by the FDIC. Coverage under this provision will begin on&#13;December 31, 2010 and end on December 31, 2012.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0.3in 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company has not experienced any losses in such accounts&#13;and believes its cash balances are not exposed to any significant risk.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: top; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 1in; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;As of March 30, 2012, the Company had funds on deposit in&#13;the amount of $286,109 in one financial institution comprised of the following:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 80%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin-left: 1in"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: bottom; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 1%; text-align: left; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;$&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="width: 10%; text-align: right; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;121,158&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="width: 1%; text-align: left; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: bottom; background-color: White; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="text-align: left; padding-bottom: 1pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;Interest bearing account&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="padding-bottom: 1pt; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; text-align: left"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; text-align: right"&gt;164,951&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="padding-bottom: 1pt; text-align: left; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: bottom; background-color: rgb(204,238,255); font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="padding-bottom: 2.5pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="padding-bottom: 2.5pt; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="border-bottom: Black 2.5pt double; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; text-align: left"&gt;$&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="border-bottom: Black 2.5pt double; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; text-align: right"&gt;286,109&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="padding-bottom: 2.5pt; text-align: left; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company has not experienced any losses in such accounts&#13;and believes its cash balances are not exposed to any significant risk.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Property, Plant and Equipment:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Property, plant and equipment is stated at cost less accumulated&#13;depreciation and amortization. The Company provides for depreciation and amortization using the Double Declining Balance method&#13;over the estimated useful lives (5-7 years) of the related assets.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Maintenance and repair expenditures are charged to operations,&#13;and renewals and betterments are capitalized. Items of property, plant and equipment, which are sold, retired or otherwise disposed&#13;of, are removed from the asset and accumulated depreciation or amortization account. Any gain or loss thereon is either credited&#13;or charged to operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Income Taxes:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company follows the policy of treating investment tax&#13;credits as a reduction in the provision for federal income tax in the year in which the credit arises or may be utilized. Deferred&#13;income taxes arise from temporary differences resulting from different depreciation methods used for financial and income tax purposes.&#13;The Company has adopted the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&amp;#147;FASB&amp;#148;) Accounting Standards Codification (&amp;#147;ASC&amp;#148;)&#13;Topic 740, Income Taxes which includes the provisions of Statement of Financial Accounting Standards (SFAS) No. 109, &amp;#147;Accounting&#13;for Income Taxes&amp;#148;.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Net Income Per Share:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company has adopted the provisions of ASC Topic&#13;260, Earnings Per Share which includes the provisions of SFAS No. 128, &amp;#147;Earnings Per Share&amp;#148;, which requires the&#13;disclosure of &amp;#147;basic&amp;#148; and &amp;#147;diluted&amp;#148; earnings (loss) per share. Basic earnings per share is computed by&#13;dividing net income by the weighted average number of common shares outstanding during each period. Diluted earnings per&#13;share is similar to basic earnings per share except that the weighted average number of common shares outstanding is&#13;increased to reflect the dilutive effect of potential common shares, such as those issuable upon the exercise of stock or&#13;warrants, as if they had been issued. For the years ended March 30, 2012 and March 25, 2011, there were no items of potential&#13;dilution that would impact on the computation of diluted earnings or loss per share.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: center"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;Fair Value of Financial Instruments:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The carrying value of the Company&amp;#146;s financial instruments,&#13;consisting of accounts receivable, accounts payable, and borrowings, approximate their fair value due to the relatively short maturity&#13;(three months) of these instruments.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Use of Estimates:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The preparation of financial statements in conformity with&#13;generally accepted accounting principles requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts&#13;of assets and liabilities, revenues and expenses, and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial&#13;statements. Actual amounts could differ from those estimates.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Impairment of Long-Lived Assets:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company has adopted the provisions of ASC Topic 360,&#13;Property, Plant and Equipment-Impairment or Disposal of Long Lived Assets which includes the provisions of SFAS No. 144, &amp;#147;Accounting&#13;For The Impairment of Long-Lived Assets And Long-Lived Assets To Be Disposed Of&amp;#148;, and requires that long-lived assets and&#13;certain identifiable intangibles to be held and used by an entity be reviewed for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances&#13;indicate that the carrying amount of an asset may not be recoverable. The Company has adopted SFAS No. 144. There were no long-lived&#13;asset impairments recognized by the Company for the years ended March 30, 2012 and March 25, 2011.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Reporting Comprehensive Income:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company has adopted the provisions of ASC Topic 220,&#13;Comprehensive Income which includes the provisions of SFAS No. 130, &amp;#147;Reporting Comprehensive Income&amp;#148;. This Statement&#13;established standards for reporting and display of comprehensive income and its components (revenues, expenses, gains and losses)&#13;in an entity&amp;#146;s financial statements. This Statement requires an entity to classify items of other comprehensive income by&#13;their nature in a financial statement and display the accumulated balance of other comprehensive income separately from retained&#13;earnings and additional paid-in capital in the equity section of a statement of financial position. There were no material items&#13;of comprehensive income to report for the years ended March 30, 2012 and March 25, 2011.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Segment Information:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company has adopted the provisions of ASC Topic 280,&#13;Segment Reporting which includes the Provisions of SFAS No. 131, &amp;#147;Disclosures About Segment of An Enterprise and Related&#13;Information.&amp;#148; This Statement requires public enterprises to report financial and descriptive information about its reportable&#13;operating segments and establishes standards for related disclosures about product and services, geographic areas, and major customers.&#13;The adoption of ASC Topic 280 did not affect the Company&amp;#146;s presentation of its results of operations or financial position.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;Research and Development:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company provides personalized engineering services to&#13;its customers by designing connectors for specific customer applications. The employment of electromechanical engineers is the&#13;anticipated cornerstone of the Company&amp;#146;s future growth. The Company maintains a testing laboratory where its engineers experiment&#13;with new connector designs based on changes in technology and in an attempt to create innovative, more efficient connector designs.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in; text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company did not expend any funds on, nor receive any&#13;revenues related to, customer sponsored research and development activities relating to the development of new designs, techniques&#13;and the improvement of existing designs during the years ended March 30, 2012 and March 25, 2011, respectively.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Effect of New Accounting Pronouncements:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;In June 2009, the FASB issued SFAS No. 168, &amp;#147;The FASB&#13;Accounting Standards Codification and Hierarchy of Generally Accepted Principles - a Replacement of FASB Statement No. 162 (&amp;#147;SFAS&#13;No. 168&amp;#148;). SFAS No. 168 establishes the ASC as the source of authoritative accounting principles recognized by the FASB to&#13;be applied in the preparation of financial statements in conformity with GAAP.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in; color: blue"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;Rules and interpretive releases of the SEC under the authority&#13;of Federal securities laws are also sources of authoritative GAAP for SEC registrants. All guidance contained in the ASC carries&#13;an equal level of authority.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The ASC superseded all existing non-SEC accounting and reporting&#13;standards. The FASB will not issue new standards in the form of any SFAS, FASB Staff Positions or Emerging Issues Task Force Abstracts.&#13;Instead, the FASB will issue Accounting Standards Updates (&amp;#147;ASU&amp;#148;) that will serve to update the ASC, provide background&#13;information about the guidance and provide the bases for conclusions on the change(s) in the ASC. The adoption of SFAS No. 168&#13;did not have an impact upon the Company&amp;#146;s financial position, results of operations or cash flows.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;In May 2009, the FASB issued guidance now codified as ASC&#13;Topic 855, &amp;#147;Subsequent Events&amp;#148;, which provides authoritative accounting literature related to evaluating subsequent&#13;events. ASC 855 is similar to current guidance with some exceptions that are not intended to result in significant change to current&#13;practice. ASC 855 defines subsequent events and also requires the disclosure of the date through which an entity has evaluated&#13;subsequent events and the basis for that date. The provisions of ASC 855 are effective for interim or annual financial periods&#13;ending after June 15, 2009. The Company has adopted the provisions of ASC 855 effective as of September 30, 2009 and its adoption&#13;did not have a material impact on the Company&amp;#146;s financial position, results of operations, cash flows or its required disclosures&#13;in its Form 10-K. The Company has evaluated subsequent events through June 22, 2012.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;In April 2009, the FASB issued FSP FAS No. 107-1&#13;and Accounting Principles Board (&amp;#147;APB&amp;#148;) Opinion No. 28-1, Interim Disclosures about Fair Value of Financial Instruments&amp;#148;,&#13;which amends SFAS No. 107, Disclosures about Fair Value of Financial Instruments and requires disclosures about the fair value&#13;of financial instruments for interim reporting periods as well as in annual financial statements. FSP FAS No. 107-1 and APB No.&#13;28-1 also amend APB Opinion No. 28, Interim Financial Reporting, to require these disclosures in all interim financial statements.&#13;FSP FAS No. 107-1 and APB No. 28-1 are effective for interim reporting periods ending after June 15, 2009. The guidance of FSP&#13;FAS No. 107-1 and APB No. 28-1 is now included in ASC Topic 825, Financial Statements. The adoption of FSP FAS No. 107-1 and APB&#13;No. 28-1 did not have a material impact on the Company&amp;#146;s financial position, results of operations or cash flows.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in; color: blue"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company has adopted the provisions of ASC Topic 740,&#13;Income Taxes which includes the provisions of Financial Accounting Standards Board Interpretation No.48 (&amp;#147;FIN 48&amp;#148;),&#13;&amp;#147;Accounting for Uncertainty in Income Taxes - an interpretation of FASB Statement No. 109&amp;#148;, which clarifies the accounting&#13;for uncertainty in income taxes recognized in an entity&amp;#146;s financial statements in accordance with FASB Statement No.109,&#13;&amp;#147;Accounting for Income Taxes&amp;#148;. ASC 740 prescribes a recognition threshold and measurement attribute for the financial&#13;statement disclosures of tax positions taken or expected to be taken in an income tax filing.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The evaluation of a tax position is a two step process.&#13;The first step requires an entity to determine whether it is more likely than not that a tax position will be sustained upon examination&#13;based upon the technical merits of the position. The second step requires an entity to recognize in the financial statements each&#13;tax position that meets the more likely than not criteria, measured at the largest amount of benefit that has a greater than fifty&#13;percent likelihood of being recognized. ASC 740 also provides guidance on de-recognition, classification, interest and penalties,&#13;accounting for interim periods, disclosure and transition.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company believes that with its adoption of ASC Topic&#13;740, that the income tax positions taken by it did not have a material effect on the financial statements for the year ended March&#13;30, 2012.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company has adopted the provisions of ASC Topic 820,&#13;Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures which includes the provisions of SFAS No.157, &amp;#147;Fair Value Measurements&amp;#148;, which&#13;enhances existing guidance for measuring assets and liabilities using fair value. ASC Topic 820 and SFAS No. 157 provide a single&#13;definition of fair value, together with a framework for measuring it, and require additional disclosure about the use of fair value&#13;to measure assets and liabilities. The Company does not believe that ASC Topic 820 will have a material impact on its financial&#13;statements.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company has adopted the provisions of ASC Topic 825,&#13;Financial Instruments, which includes the provisions of SFAS No. 159 (&amp;#147;SFAS 159&amp;#148;) &amp;#147;The Fair Value Option for&#13;Financial Assets and Financial Liabilities&amp;#148;, providing companies with an option to report selected financial assets and liabilities&#13;at fair value. The objective of ASC Topic 825 and SFAS 159 is to reduce both complexity in accounting for&#13;financial instruments and the volatility in earnings caused&#13;by measuring related assets and liabilities differently. They also require entities to display the fair value of those assets and&#13;liabilities. The Company has chosen to use fair value on the face of the balance sheet. The Company does not believe that ASC Topic&#13;825 will have a material impact on its financial statements.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock>

    <us-gaap:IncomeTaxDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="From2011-03-26to2012-03-30">&lt;p style="margin: 0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="width: 100%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: top; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;td style="width: 1in; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Note 7 - &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;INCOME TAXES:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The Company accounts for income taxes under the provisions&#13;of ASC Topic 740, Income Taxes which includes the provisions of SFAS No. 109 (&amp;#147;SFAS 109&amp;#148;). Under SFAS 109, deferred&#13;income tax assets or liabilities are computed based upon the temporary differences between the financial statement and income tax&#13;bases of assets and liabilities using the currently enacted marginal income tax rates. Deferred income tax expenses or credits&#13;are based on the changes in the deferred income tax assets or liabilities from period to period.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0 0 0 1in"&gt;The provision for income taxes consists of the following:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: center; text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="width: 100%; font: bold 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: top; During the year ended March&#13;25, 2011 approximately 38% of the Company&amp;#146;s total revenues were earned from four customers. Total sales to these customers&#13;were approximately $6,687,000 and $5,240,000. Of these, two customers accounted for 12.15% and 11.83% of the Company&amp;#146;s sales&#13;respectively. As of March 30, 2012, amounts due from three customers represented 28% of the total balance of accounts receivable.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:ConcentrationRiskDisclosureTextBlock>

width: 90%; font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin-left: 1in"&gt;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: bottom; background-color: rgb(204,238,255); font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;td nowrap="nowrap" style="padding-bottom: 2.5pt;
